quizzes.question:
What is the result of the following code if the HTML contains <p>1</p>?
$("p").append("2");
$("p").prepend("1");

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Adding Content[/h1]

The [b]append()[/b] method inserts content AT THE END of the selected HTML element.
For example:
[b]HTML[/b]: [code format="html" ]<p id="demo">Hi </p>[/code]
[b]JS:[/b] [code format="js" codeId="1112"]$(function() {
  $("#demo").[b]append[/b]("David");
});
//Outputs "Hi David"[/code]
[note]Similarly, the [b]prepend[/b]() method inserts content AT THE BEGINNING of the selected element. 
You can also use HTML markup for the content.[/note]

[h1]Adding Content[/h1]

The jQuery [b]after[/b]() and [b]before[/b]() methods insert content AFTER and BEFORE the selected HTML element.
For example:
[b]HTML[/b]: [code format="html" ]<p id="demo">Hi</p>[/code]
[b]JS[/b]: [code format="js" codeId="1113"]$(function() {
  $("#demo").[b]before[/b]("<i>Some Title</i>");   
  $("#demo").[b]after[/b]("<b>Welcome</b>");
});[/code]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to create a new <span> element and append it to the element with id="txt".
[!raw!]
var a = $("<{0}></span>");
{1}("#txt").append({2});

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Adding New Elements[/h1]

The [b]append[/b](), [b]prepend[/b](), [b]before[/b]() and [b]after[/b]() methods can also be used to add newly created elements.
The easiest way of creating a new HTML element with jQuery is the following: [code format="js" ]var txt = $("<p></p>").text("Hi"); [/code]
The code above creates a new [b]<p>[/b] element, which contains the text Hi and assigns it to a variable called [b]txt[/b].
Now, we can use that variable as a parameter of the above mentioned methods to add it to our HTML, for example:
[b]HTML[/b]: [code format="html" ]<p id="demo">Hello</p>[/code]
[b]JS[/b]: [code format="raw" codeId="1114"]$(function() {
  var txt = $("<p></p>").text("Hi");
  $("#demo").[b]after[/b](txt);
});[/code]
This will insert the newly created <p> element after the #demo paragraph.
You can also specify multiple elements as arguments for the [b]before()[/b], [b]after()[/b], [b]append()[/b], [b]prepend()[/b] methods by separating them using commas: $("#demo").append(var1, var2, var3).
[note]The above mentioned syntax for creating elements can be used to create any new HTML element, for example [b]$("<div></div>")[/b] creates a new div.[/note]
